        <strong class='text-white text-2xl'>Accelerated bone loss after menopause: Type 1 primary osteoporosis</strong><br/><br/>
        In the first 5 to 7 years after menopause, reduced estrogen causes faster bone mass loss.<br/><br/>
        Why does this happen?<br/><br/>
        An imbalance is created between bone resorption and production at both estrogen and estradiol levels, which drops by 10-15% and estrone by 35%. This causes the calcium that is normally well "stored" in bones to begin releasing into the blood. To prevent too much calcium accumulation, the body increases its elimination through urine, absorbs less calcium from food and adjusts the production of certain hormones related to its management.<br/><br/>
